To extract the watch ID (e.g., "WLHK-U7QK-LX9W") from a YouTube URL using regular expressions, you can use the following pattern:

^https://www.youtube.com/(?:watch\?v)?([a-zA-Z0-9]+)($|[/?&])

This pattern matches the entire YouTube URL, starting with the protocol ("^https:") and ending at the end of the string ($). The first capture group matches the video title or description, capturing up to 20 characters in either case using brackets ([...]). The second capture group captures the YouTube Watch ID, which is composed of alphanumeric characters, spaces, dashes, and underscores. The third capture group allows for optional additional parameters after the? mark, including search terms, access restrictions, etc. (using |), and the fourth capture group specifies that the match should be an absolute URL ($) rather than a relative one (/?).

Here's a brief explanation of each component of the regex:

    ^http://www.youtube.com/: this part defines the start of the URL by matching the beginning of the line ($). It also prefixes all parts of the URL with http:// so that it only matches URLs that begin with HTTP or HTTPS.

    (?:watch\?v)?: this is a non-capturing group that allows for the presence or absence of the query parameter "watch"? followed by any number of sub-parameters (in lowercase letters). This ensures that the regex will correctly handle both valid Youtube URLs with the `"watch?"` parameter as well as invalid ones without it.

    ([a-zA-Z0-9]+)(\s*)($|[/?&]): this is the main capturing group that matches the YouTube Watch ID. The first parenthesis () captures any amount of white space (\s*) before the final occurrence of $ or "/". The second parentheses capture everything between the first two slashes (/) until the closing ) character. Finally, the dollar sign ($) indicates that the whole matched portion should be interpreted as a URL rather than text.

    ((?:.*\()?): this non-capturing group follows the main capturing group but captures anything preceding the opening parenthesis ((.). The parentheses allow us to capture non-whitespace characters before the opening parenthesis (.*), while still ensuring that we don't capture garbage data elsewhere in the URL.

    ([\w.-]+)$: this is the last capturing group that matches the remainder of the URL after the WatchID. The \w character class represents alphabetic characters, digits, hyphens, and underscores. The + quantifier means that there can occur 1 or more occurrences of this class within the whole matched portion of the URL.

    (?<!\/)/: this negative lookbehind condition asserts that the immediately proceeding backslash (\) cannot be directly matched (it would have already been matched by the previous step). This ensures that even if the user provides an unnecessary forward slash during input, our Regular Expression will not mistakenly treat it as the closing token for the URL.

